Clair-d'Arcey, Eure, Haute-Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1031–":"1031–Deceased","1035–1082":"1035–1082","1065–1118":"1065–1118","1070–1123":"1070–1123","1031–Male":"1031–Deceased","1118":"1118","1123":"1123","1035":"1035","1065":"1065","1031":"1031","Cir 1065":"1065","Abt 1070":"about 1070","1082":"1082","ABT 1061":"about 1061","1070":"1070","Dieppe, Normandy, France":"Dieppe, Normandy, France","Dieppe, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, France":"Dieppe, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France","Nocton, Lincolnshire, England":"Nocton, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","France":"France","Saint-Clair-d'Arcey, Eure, Normandy, France":"Saint-Clair-d'Arcey, Eure, Upper Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"d’Arcy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Eamon, Brendan, Eamonn, Maeve, Malachy, Niamh, Seamus.  French Gisele, Julien, Normand, Alain, Armand, Cecile, Clemence, Dominique, Emile, Gilles, Jean-Paul, Laure.","English (Lancashire) and Irish: of Norman origin, a habitational name from Arcy in Manche, France, with fused preposition <i>d(e)</i> ‘from’.","Irish: in Ireland, this is generally the Norman name (see 1 above), established in Meath by Sir William <i>D'Arcy</i> in the 1360s, but it was also adopted for <b>Ó Dorchaidhe</b> ‘descendant of the dark one’, from <i>dorcha</i> ‘dark, gloomy’, a Connacht name that fell together with the Norman surname, which was introduced by Sir William <i>D'Arcy</i> and Sir John <i>D'Arcy</i>, Chief Justiciar of Ireland in the 14th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Darsey","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Darcy   2.","Scottish: from Dairsie in Fife."]},{"name":"Darcey","meanings":["English (of Norman origin) and Irish (Tipperary): variant of   Darcy  ."]}]},{"name":"Norman","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic origin, from <i>nord</i> ‘north’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’, i.e. ‘Norseman’. This name was in use in England before the Conquest, and was reinforced by its use among the Norman invaders themselves. The Normans were the inhabitants of Normandy in northern France, whose name is a reference to the Vikings who took control of the region in the 9th century. In the 11th and 12th centuries they achieved remarkable conquests, including not only Britain but also Sicily, southern Italy, and Antioch. In the Scottish Highlands it is used as the Anglicized equivalent of Tormod ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Norman d’Arcy was born in 1031, in Dieppe, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France. He married Adelina A Court about 1061, in Dieppe, Normandy, France. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in Nocton, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1031–":"1031–Surnud","1035–1082":"1035–1082","1065–1118":"1065–1118","1070–1123":"1070–1123","1031–Male":"1031–Surnud","1118":"1118","1123":"1123","1035":"1035","1065":"1065","1031":"1031","Cir 1065":"1065","Abt 1070":"umbes 1070","1082":"1082","ABT 1061":"umbes 1061","1070":"1070","Dieppe, Normandy, France":"Dieppe, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Dieppe, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, France":"Dieppe, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Nocton, Lincolnshire, England":"Nocton, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","France":"Prantsusmaa","Saint-Clair-d'Arcey, Eure, Normandy, France":"Saint-Clair-d'Arcey, Eure, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1031–":"1031–Kuollut","1035–1082":"1035–1082","1065–1118":"1065–1118","1070–1123":"1070–1123","1031–Male":"1031–Kuollut","1118":"1118","1123":"1123","1035":"1035","1065":"1065","1031":"1031","Cir 1065":"1065","Abt 1070":"noin 1070","1082":"1082","ABT 1061":"noin 1061","1070":"1070","Dieppe, Normandy, France":"Dieppe, Normandie, Ranska","Dieppe, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, France":"Dieppe, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Ranska","Nocton, Lincolnshire, England":"Nocton, Lincolnshire, 